40|$|During the {{re-entry}} {{phase of}} a manned satellite, some equipment for continuous on-board <b>indication</b> of <b>position</b> will be required. Since radio and radar may be useless during part of the re-entry, inertial guidance equipment may be required. Such equipment, however, has an inherent instability in the computation of altitude. The present study of an inertial guidance system shows that for reasonable values of initial-condition errors and equipment biases. the resultant <b>position</b> <b>indication</b> errors will not become excessive unless the re-entry maneuver time is greater than 45 minutes to an hour. Further, the <b>position</b> <b>indication</b> error caused by accelerometer uncertainties can be reduced by switching off the accelerometers until their output becomes significantly greater than their uncertainty...|$|R
